# OpenPLC project structure (mandatory)

This rule applies to any project that follows the openplc/brewery layout (a stand-alone OpenPLC project rooted at a single folder containing `pous/`, `project.json`, `build/`, and optionally `pi-sidecar/`, `docs/`, `tools/`, `devices/`, `backups/`).

## Source-of-truth files

- **`pous/programs/main.ld`** — the editor-source ladder program. Authoritative for control flow.
- **`pous/function-blocks/*.st`** — Structured Text function-block POUs (`FB_*` convention). Authoritative for reusable logic.
- **`pous/functions/*.st`** — Structured Text function POUs. Distinct from function blocks; see `03-openplc-function-vs-function-block.mdc`.
- **`project.json`** — OpenPLC editor project file. Authoritative for `debugVariables.pous.main` (the editor's pre-selected watch list) and task/instance configuration.
- **`devices/configuration.json`** (when present) — frozen device/transport configuration (e.g. RTU baud rate, slave id, RS-485 pin).

## Generated / non-authoritative files

- **`build/...`** — generated. Do NOT edit. Do NOT assume current unless intentionally regenerated.
  - `build/<target>/src/program.st` is the raw editor compile output.
  - `build/<target>/src/program.runtime-upload.st` is the prepared upload artifact (see `08-pi-modbus-contract-and-runtime-upload.mdc`).
- **`backups/...`** — dated snapshots. Do NOT rewrite. Use git history or a dedicated legacy branch for older context.

## Hard rules

- Do **not** edit anything under `build/`. Treat it as cache.
- Do **not** rewrite anything under `backups/`. They are historical artifacts.
- Do **not** upload `main.ld` to the OpenPLC Runtime web UI. The runtime expects flat Structured Text (see `08-pi-modbus-contract-and-runtime-upload.mdc`).
- Ladder-structure changes should preferably go through the OpenPLC graphical editor, not direct `main.ld` edits. The exceptions (allowed direct-edit cases) are: declaration changes and `project.json` debug-visibility tweaks.
- After any direct edit to `main.ld` or `project.json`, **reopening OpenPLC is the current expected way to force a reload from disk**. Communicate this step explicitly to the developer rather than assuming a hot reload.

## Editor watch-list (`project.json` `debugVariables`)

- `data.debugVariables.pous.main` is the authoritative pre-selection. Editing it is preferred over clicking variables one-by-one in the OpenPLC UI.
- When preparing a watch list for a test, include the **full mutually exclusive state** you intend to verify — not only the variable expected to be `TRUE`. Adjacent state variables matter; omitting them is the common failure mode.

